solution: ```class Solution {
    int m, n, total;
    unordered_map<int,int> map;
public:
    Solution(int m, int n) : m(m), n(n), total(m * n) {}

    vector<int> flip() {
        int idx = rand() % total;
        int val = map.count(idx) ? map[idx] : idx;
        int last = --total;
        map[idx] = map.count(last) ? map[last] : last;
        return {val / n, val % n};
    }

    void reset() {
        total = m * n;
        map.clear();
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(1) amortized per flip/reset
space complexity: O(k) where k is the number of flipped cells
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses Fisher-Yates inside a hash map to map virtual indices to actual indices, ensuring uniform randomness with one rand() call per flip and O(1) expected time.

